    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Relatively deep-bodied species with an arching back and small, downward-facing mouth with a single short thick barbel under chin. Front (spinose) portion of the dorsal fin tall and triangular and separated from the lower (rayed) posterior section by a deep notch. Juveniles more commonly seen and are light brown with a broad dark-brown vertical band and narrower horizontal band along flank. Adults develop longitudinal wavy dark bands along back and sides.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_3866",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Up to 43 cm total length.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_3867",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Widespread in Mediterranean, eastern Atlantic and western Indian Ocean.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Northern Namibia to East London, rarely off KwaZulu-Natal.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_3868",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Adults mainly found offshore and are caught by the trawl fisheries down to a depth of at least 300 m. Juveniles can be found close inshore over sand or in caves. Usually seen singly or in small groups.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_3869",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Predatory, feeding mostly on shrimps, worms and other invertebrates.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_3870",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Matures at a length of 20â€“25 cm and spawns August to February. The transparent, buoyant eggs are releases into the water column and develop in the plankton.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_3871",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>Easily confused with Slender baardman <i>U. robinsoni,</i> which occurs from Cape Point eastwards and has similar habits. However, that species grows to a much larger size of 99 cm and is usually dark brown with wavy oblique white lines along sides of body (but can change colour to silvery within a few seconds!).</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_3872",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Further reading / References",
            "shortText": "Branch, G, Griffiths, CL, Branch, M & Beckley, L (2016). Two Oceans: A Guide to the Marine Life of Southern Africa. (Fifth edition) Struik Nature, Cape Town. (p. 300).<br><br>Heemstra, P & Heemstra E (2004). Coastal Fishes of South Africa. NISC, Grahamstown. (p. 273).<br><br>Heemstra, P, Heemstra, E, Ebert, D, Holleman, W & Randall, J (2022). Coastal Fishes of the Western Indian Ocean. National Research Foundation & South African Institute for Aquatic Biodiversity, South Africa. Volume 3 (p. 412). <br><br>Smith, MM & Heemstra, P (eds.) (2003). Smith's Sea Fishes. Struik Publishers, Cape Town (p. 619).<br><br>Zsilavecz, G (2005). Coastal Fishes of the Cape Peninsula and False Bay. SURG, Cape Town (p. 44).",
